Elon Musk is forced to leave the post of head of the board of directors of Tesla
The US Securities and Exchange Commission and Tesla founder Elon Musk settled their dispute in a fraud case.
It is reported by CNBC News.
According to the channel, as part of the agreements reached, Musk will have to leave the post of head of the board of directors of Tesla.
At the same time, the commission allowed Musk to retain the post of head of Tesla.
As noted, the founder of Tesla will also have to pay an administrative fine of $ 20 million.
A similar amount will be charged from Tesla.
At the same time, the money will be distributed among the affected investors.
In addition, the company must appoint two independent directors.
Elon Musk is an American entrepreneur who is included in the list of the 50 richest people in the world according to Forbes magazine.
He is the head of the space corporation SpaceX, the neurotechological company Neuralink and the developer of electric cars Tesla, as well as the co-founder of Paypal.
The US Securities and Exchange Commission previously sued Tesla CEO Elon Musk because of his message posted on Twitter about a possible buyout of the company.
Last month, Musk announced plans to make Tesla a private company and buy back all shares on the stock exchange at a fixed price of $ 420.
The share price of $ 420 was established allegedly "because of the importance of this number in the culture of marijuana," Bloomberg reported earlier, citing Stephen Peikin, co-director of the commission's security department.
At the same time, Elon Musk subsequently abandoned his plans to buy back shares.
Commenting on the lawsuit filed against him by the US Securities and Exchange Commission, the businessman said that he considers the accusations of fraud unfounded, and added that he is very disappointed and saddened by these claims.
"Honesty is the most important value in my life, and the facts will prove that I did not violate it in any way," the businessman said in an interview with CNBC.
At the same time, in August, a group of Tesla shareholders filed a class action lawsuit against Musk, complaining about the financial losses incurred.
The plaintiffs argued that the businessman's posts brought them losses.
In particular, one of the shareholders said that the tweets of the businessman were misleading, which is why sellers of Tesla shares were forced to buy securities at artificially inflated prices to cover their positions.
Also, other plaintiffs noted that Elon Musk's careless statements led to sharp fluctuations in the exchange rate.
In September, Elon Musk was accused of stock exchange fraud by the head of the research company Citron Research.
Meanwhile, if Musk could not resolve his dispute with the US Securities and Exchange Commission, he would face removal from the management of the company and even prison.
This, in particular, was stated to CNBC by the former chairman of the commission Harvey Pitt.
Musk is "not a bad guy who doesn't know how to run a car company."
