On September 30, 1928, that is, exactly 90 years ago, the British bacteriologist Alexander Fleming announced an unprecedented discovery.
The discovery of penicillin marked the beginning of the era of modern antibiotics, brought Fleming worldwide fame and made him a Nobel laureate.
By the way, the isolation of penicillin from mold fungi was not Fleming's first discovery.
A few years earlier, he, being a cold, had sown mucus from his own nose on a petri dish (this is a kind of glass lid in which experiments with bacteria are carried out) and a few days later discovered that the bacteria that were there had been destroyed.
Almost as by chance, he discovered penicillin.
Fleming's name was included in the list of the 100 most prominent personalities in the history of mankind.
His discovery, according to many scientists, changed the course of history.
With the help of penicillin, medicine began to cope with most of the oldest diseases, previously considered incurable - tuberculosis, syphilis, gangrene ...
When, shortly after receiving the Nobel Prize, Fleming arrived in the French capital in 1945, Parisian newspapers wrote: "To defeat fascism and liberate France, he did more than dozens of divisions."
According to experts, Fleming's discovery of the world's first antibiotic saved the lives of more than 200 million people on Earth.
Alexander Fleming died at his home in London in 1955 of a heart attack.
He was cremated and a week later his ashes were buried in London's famous St Paul's Cathedral.
Where, by the way, my wife and I drew attention to this wordy Russian-speaking guide.
A few years later, we had a chance to observe the statue of Alexander Fleming in full growth in the most unexpected place in the capital of Spain.
