Kosachev: At the 73rd session of the UN General Assembly, the topic of Russia in a negative way was practically absent
The head of the Federation Council Committee on International Affairs, Konstantin Kosachev, considers the 73rd session of the UN General Assembly successful for Russia and does not exclude that it can become a turning point in the perception of the Russian Federation as an integral participant in solving global world problems.
"The uniqueness of the current 73rd session, in my opinion, lies in the fact that the rhetoric, to which we have almost become accustomed in recent years in relation to Russia, has now been much more muted," the senator said in an interview published on Sunday by Rossiyskaya Gazeta.
He explained that in previous years, russia was sometimes "designated as one of the three main threats to humanity, then along with Ebola, then along with climate change or terrorism, Russia was in this series, at least in the presentation of a group of Western countries, which spoke on this subject quite unanimously."
At the 73rd session, Kosachev emphasized, "the topic of Russia in a negative way was practically absent."
"If you carefully analyze the speech of the PRESIDENT OF THE UNITED STATES, the President of France, the speech of the Minister of Foreign Affairs of Germany, I am not taking Ukraine, Georgia, or the British, in any case, there was no choir for sure," the politician said, noting that Russia "was no longer a kind of wall against which tennis ball strikes are trained."
The head of the relevant committee of the Federation Council does not exclude that this indicates a certain trend, which, in his opinion, "will highlight the current session [of the UN General Assembly], although this trend may fully manifest itself in a year, in two, three."
"I do not rule out that the current session in some sense may be a turning point," Kosachev admitted, explaining that "there are too many examples of how with the involvement of Russia it is possible to move forward in international affairs."
As an example, he cited the situation in Syria, around Iran and North Korea.
"So far, unfortunately, this is not Ukraine, but I have no doubt that the Russian vision of the Ukrainian crisis will also be in demand over time," the parliamentarian added.
This is due to the fact, he believes, that there is "an adequate, sensible perception of Russia as not just possible - an integral participant in solving global problems of our time."
"I wouldn't want to be wrong, but I have a feeling that we are passing a point somewhere beyond which the movement will no longer be a reversal, it will be a movement forward," he added.
Another "interesting and important feeling" in this context Kosachev called "a request for a Russian vision of how the modern world should develop."
"I attended a lot of meetings of the head of the Russian delegation [at the session of the General Assembly] Foreign Minister Sergei Lavrov, I held my own meetings, and I saw with great pleasure that if a year or two or five years ago no one was interested in Russian opinion, the Russian vision of what is happening in the world, by and large, no one was interested, now the situation is different," the chairman of the Federation Council Committee said.
In his opinion, this is due to the fact that "the so-called new liberal order, which is personified with the West, does not have answers to the questions of how to solve world problems due to the obvious lack of ideas in the global space, the lack of ideas on how to solve the problems of the Middle East, the problems of terrorism, the problems of non-proliferation of nuclear weapons, the problems of migration."
"And here the demand for the Russian vision is becoming more and more obvious," Kosachev expressed confidence, stressing that he considers in this sense "the current session successful for the work of the Russian delegation, successful for Russia."
