AfD became the second most popular in Germany
The anti-immigrant Alternative for Germany is breaking another popularity record, and Angela Merkel's ratings are falling.
Apparently, the inhabitants of Germany began to seriously tire of the immigration policy of Angela Merkel, thanks to which the country became a coveted target for millions of refugees from the Middle East.
This is most clearly evidenced by the latest opinion polls, according to which the anti-immigrant party "Alternative for Germany" is becoming increasingly popular, and the positions of the ruling bloc of Merkel and Seehofer are weakening.
This week, the AfD broke another record, rising to second place in the ranking of popular sympathies.
Right-wing conservatives with 17 percent of popularity managed to bypass the Social Democrats, who have about 16 percent.
The gap of one percentage point can be attributed to a statistical error, but it is impossible not to note the fact that the AfD created in 2013 from a small group of Eurosceptic economists managed to turn into a serious political force.
Leadership in the overall standings still continues to be held by the ruling bloc of the CSU / CDU, which has about 30 percent.
However, there is a tendency to lose points - back in April, support for Angela Merkel's bloc was four percentage points higher.
The personal rating of the German Chancellor, who heads the German government for the fourth consecutive term, is also declining.
Today, 48 percent of Germans support Angela Merkel, which is 7 percent lower than last year.
We add that after the Social Democrats are the Greens (15%), the Left (11%) and the Liberals (10%).
Evolution of the "Alternative"
The Alternative for Germany party was created in September 2012 on the basis of the alternative choice 2013 group, which included immigrants from the Christian Democratic Union.
The group initially opposed the government's course, but at first it dealt only with economic issues, including the problems of the euro and interaction within the EU.
At the same time, the group opposed germany's "sponsorship" of weak EU economies, did not rule out the possibility of returning to the German mark and the country's complete exit from the European Union.
As the immigration crisis deepens, the AfD's political platform has expanded.
In 2013, the group took shape in a full-fledged party, which occupied the niche of Eurosceptics and began to harshly criticize the government for the failure of immigration policy.
In the last parliamentary elections in 2017, the AfD managed to break into the Bundestag for the first time, receiving 94 seats (out of 709).
Two representatives of the "Alternative for Germany" will receive seats in the European Parliament.
