Named the period of death of the Universe
The universe will last another 140 billion years, which is ten times the age of the observable world, which is about 13.8 billion years.
The study of an international team of scientists is posted in the library of electronic preprints arXiv.org and is aimed at publication in the journal Publications of the Astronomical Society of Japan, according to the Japanese newspaper Asahi Shimbun.
Experts came to such conclusions by observing with the help of the HSC camera (Hyper Suprime-Cam) of the Subaru telescope for about ten million galaxies.
By tracking the distribution of dark matter and dark energy, which account for more than 95 percent of the energy-mass of the observable world, scientists working within the framework of the standard cosmological model ΛCDM (Λ Cold Dark Matter), estimated the rate of expansion of the Universe, which turned out to be slightly slower than previously thought.
In a press release, the Subaru Observatory notes that the observations made it possible to obtain a detailed three-dimensional map of the distribution of matter in the Universe, and taking into account the data of the European Space Telescope Planck clarified the restrictions imposed on the parameters of ΛCDM.
In July, scientists simulated the possible death of the universe.
Three years earlier, their colleagues had presented new arguments that the observed world would cease to exist in 22 billion years as a result of the Great Divide.
