Pushing and leading - how right?
The word pressure doesn't exist.
That's right - to dominate.
The word "to press" in the sense of "to gravitate, to exert influence, to influence" exists only phonetically, because we hear the sound [a] instead of [o] in the word "to dominate".
We use this word, believing that it comes from the word "pressure".
But "pressure" and "pressure" are not only not close etymologically close, but even in some sense opposite.
See for yourself.
To dowlet (church-bookish, obsolete) means "enough, full, enough, to be sufficient for someone or something, to satisfy."
Contentment, pleasure are related words.
Previously, it still had the meaning "not to depend on anything, to have a self-sufficient meaning" - "to dominate yourself."
Old Church Slavonic "dovylti" is related to the words "to command" and "will".
