The main Macedonian oppositionist refused to vote in the referendum
In Macedonia, on Sunday, September 30, a referendum is held on the issue of an intergovernmental agreement with Greece on the renaming of the Republic of Macedonia.
Citizens are asked to answer one question: "Do you support membership in the EU and NATO by accepting the agreement between the Republic of Macedonia and the Hellenic Republic?"
Nevertheless, the leader of the leading opposition party, the Internal Macedonian Revolutionary Organization - Democratic Party for Macedonian National Unity (VMRO-DPMNE), Christian Mitskoski, said that he would not vote in the referendum.
As explained by the press secretary of the party Naum Stoilkovsky, Mickoski decided to abstain from the vote in order to express his disagreement with the treaty, which he considers "harmful".
According to the spokesman, the current referendum decides on the renaming of the country and nothing more, while the strategic goal of the party is to achieve membership in NATO and the EU.
A week ago, Macedonian President Gjorge Ivanov also refused to participate in the referendum on September 30.
He explained that he chose the name for the country 27 years ago in a referendum on independence. The Macedonian leader considers the renaming of the country a negative factor.
"A new semi-sovereign state with a new name is being created," Ivanov said.
The agreement on the new official name of the former Yugoslav republic - the Republic of North Macedonia - was signed by the foreign ministers of Macedonia and Greece on June 17 this year during a solemn ceremony on the shores of Lake Prespa, along which the border between the two countries passes.
This agreement should resolve the long-standing dispute over the name of the country, as well as Skopje's path to NATO and the EU, reminds TASS.
