Macedonians are preparing to vote in a referendum on joining the EU and NATO, subject to a change in the name of the country.
The agreement to rename the former Yugoslav Republic of Macedonia to the Republic of North Macedonia was reached on June 17 as the result of long negotiations with neighboring Greece, which refused to recognize the right of its northern neighbor to be called Macedonia, seeing in such a name an attempt on the Greek province of the same name and Greek history.
Lyupko Petkovski, political scientist: "Thanks to this agreement, Macedonia or North Macedonia gets the right to a better future, hope for social change.
And Greece will consolidate the right to its past.
There are no perfect agreements.
They arise as a result of difficult compromises that cannot make absolutely everyone happy."
The renaming of the country is advocated by the ruling Social Democrats, led by Prime Minister Zoran Zaev.
Against - the conservative opposition and the country's President Gheorghe Ivanov.
According to journalist Tsvetin Chilimanov, it makes no sense for Macedonia to join the EU - it is enough to have a partnership with it: "Many of those who do not like the agreement believe that the current socialist government led by Zaev was imposed from the outside in order to change the name of the country.
But this decision will entail negative consequences.
First of all, the loss of sovereignty.
Obviously, there are countries that would not like Macedonia to remain one of the sovereign countries in the Balkans."
Fei Dulgeri, Euronews: "The former Yugoslav Republic of Macedonia faces the biggest challenge in its history.
The country was at a crossroads.
The choice that the citizens of Macedonia will make will determine the future not only of the Balkans, but also of Europe as a whole."
The Ministry of Finance of the Russian Federation predicted the ruble exchange rate for 17 years ahead
The Ministry of Finance of Russia expects a gradual weakening of the ruble - up to 73.9 rubles. per dollar by 2031-2035, follows from the draft long-term budget forecast submitted to the State Duma along with the draft federal budget.
In 2021-2025, the ruble exchange rate, according to the forecast, will be 66.4 rubles per dollar, in 2026-2030 - 71.1 rubles, and in the next five years - 73.9.
The agency notes that these figures are the nominal rate.
The real effective exchange rate (an indicator that takes into account the change in the exchange rates of the countries that are the main trading partners of the Russian Federation) will remain stable, officials assure.
As for inflation, until 2020 it will be 3.5%, and then stabilize at about 4%, according to the Ministry of Finance.
